*What changed:* re-centred on the chain EVT → max-stable → Brown–Resnick/variogram → composite likelihood → Godambe/bootstrap → diagnostics → seasonal. Smith/Schlather positioned briefly against BR. Nonparametrics reframed as diagnostics. POT/declustering paragraphs removed.

```latex
\section{Literature Review}\label{sec:literature}

This review sets out the components the thesis combines: extreme-value theory and max-stability, max-stable process models for spatial extremes, the Brown--Resnick process and its variogram parametrisation, pairwise composite likelihood, inference for composite-likelihood estimators, and the nonparametric dependence summaries used here as diagnostics. Each is discussed in terms of what it contributes to estimating and comparing season-specific extremal dependence.

\subsection{Extreme-value theory and spatial extremes}\label{sec:lit-evt}

Extreme-value theory describes the tail rather than the bulk of a distribution. For scalar maxima, the Fisher--Tippett--Gnedenko theorem \citep{fisher1928,gnedenko1943} states that any non-degenerate limit of affinely normalised sample maxima is generalised extreme value (GEV); \citet{dehaan2006} give the modern treatment, including the related peaks-over-threshold limit. This justifies modelling marginal extremes by a GEV or generalised Pareto law and motivates transforming each station's margin to a common extreme-value scale before any dependence is modelled, so that dependence is separated from marginal differences.

The marginal limit is silent on how extremes at different sites occur together. For maxima observed over space, the limiting objects are max-stable processes, which arise as pointwise maxima of independent replications of a random field and extend the GEV limit from a scalar to a field \citep{dehaan2006}. Extremal dependence then becomes a spatial object, a function of location and distance. \citet{davison2012} review the area and stress that a model fitting marginal extremes well may still misrepresent joint extremes; this is the reason the thesis models the dependence directly rather than inferring it from marginal fits. Ordinary covariance is not the relevant summary, because it is dominated by the bulk and need not describe the joint tail.

\subsection{Max-stable process models}\label{sec:lit-maxstable}

Several stationary max-stable families are available. \citet{smith1990} introduced a max-stable model with a deterministic storm profile, and \citet{schlather2002} proposed a more flexible construction based on a stationary parent process. Both are limited as models of how dependence decays: the Smith model implies overly smooth, near-deterministic extremal surfaces, and the Schlather model cannot approach independence at long range. The Brown--Resnick process \citep{brown1977,kabluchko2009} avoids both limitations: its extremal dependence is governed by the variogram of an underlying Gaussian process with stationary increments, ranges from complete dependence at zero distance to independence at long range, and is determined by a small number of interpretable parameters. \citet{davison2012} use it as the leading stationary model for spatial extremes, which is why it is the model estimated here.

\subsection{The Brown--Resnick process and its variogram}\label{sec:lit-br}

\citet{kabluchko2009} characterise stationary Brown--Resnick fields through negative-definite functions, equivalently through the variogram of the underlying process. With an isotropic powered-exponential variogram
\[
      \gamma(d)=\Bigl(\frac{d}{\rho}\Bigr)^{\alpha},
      \qquad \rho>0,\ \alpha\in(0,2],
\]
the range \(\rho\) sets how slowly extremal dependence decays with distance --- a larger \(\rho\) is a larger spatial footprint of extremes --- and \(\alpha\) sets the smoothness of that decay; isotropy means dependence depends on distance alone. The implied bivariate distribution is of H\"usler--Reiss type and gives the extremal coefficient in closed form, which makes \(\rho\) directly comparable across groups. For the thesis this is the operative point: a seasonal difference in spatial footprint becomes a difference in \(\rho\), so winter storms with broad footprints and summer convective events with narrow ones correspond to \(\rho_{\mathrm W}>\rho_{\mathrm S}\). \citet{davison2013} delimit the scope of such models: Brown--Resnick fields are asymptotically dependent at all finite distances, whereas environmental extremes can be asymptotically independent, so the model may overstate dependence at the highest levels. This is why the thesis reports nonparametric tail diagnostics alongside the fit.

\subsection{Pairwise composite likelihood}\label{sec:lit-cl}

Full-likelihood inference for max-stable processes is generally infeasible: the joint density of the field at \(N\) sites is a sum over all partitions of the sites, which grows super-exponentially in \(N\) \citep{padoan2010}. \citet{padoan2010} replace the full likelihood by a pairwise composite likelihood,
\[
      \ell(\vartheta)=\sum_{i<j}\sum_{t}\log f_{ij}\bigl(z_{i,t},z_{j,t};\vartheta\bigr),
\]
where \(f_{ij}\) is the bivariate density implied by the model and \(\vartheta=(\rho,\alpha)\); maximising \(\ell\) gives a consistent and asymptotically normal estimator. This is the composite- or pseudo-likelihood idea familiar in econometrics, replacing an intractable joint objective by a tractable sum of low-dimensional ones. \citet{huser2013} study composite likelihood specifically for the Brown--Resnick process, including the bivariate density and the option of censoring contributions below a high threshold so that the fit targets the joint tail. The thesis uses the pairwise estimator of \citet{padoan2010} with the Brown--Resnick bivariate density, estimated separately by season.

\subsection{Inference for composite-likelihood estimators}\label{sec:lit-inference}

Because \(\ell\) is composite, ordinary likelihood standard errors are invalid. The asymptotic covariance is instead the inverse Godambe (sandwich) information \(H J^{-1} H\), with \(H\) the sensitivity and \(J\) the variability of the composite score \citep{padoan2010}. This requires estimating \(J\) and assumes independent replicates. For the present data the replicates are daily maxima, which remain dependent within a multi-day storm, so the thesis uses a seasonal-year block bootstrap for the reported uncertainty and for the winter--summer comparison: resampling whole season-years preserves both the within-storm serial dependence and the cross-station dependence among pairs sharing a station. The Godambe form is used as a theoretical reference and as a cross-check under the independence assumption, not as the basis for the reported intervals.

\subsection{Nonparametric extremal-dependence diagnostics}\label{sec:lit-diagnostics}

Three nonparametric pairwise summaries are used to check the fit. The extremal coefficient \(\theta(s_i,s_j)\in[1,2]\) measures the effective number of independent sites in a pair; the \(F\)-madogram of \citet{cooley2006} estimates it from transformed margins without a parametric model. The finite-level tail-dependence coefficient \(\chi_u(s_i,s_j)\) is the probability of joint exceedance of a high level, and \citet{coles1999} introduce \(\chi\) and \(\bar\chi\) to separate asymptotic dependence from asymptotic independence. These are standard descriptive tools for extremal dependence; here they are diagnostics, used to check whether the fitted Brown--Resnick curve is consistent with the pairwise estimates across distance and whether dependence weakens at the highest levels in a way the model cannot represent. \citet{davison2013} and \citet{huser2020} survey the asymptotic-independence alternatives that these diagnostics would point to if the fit failed.

\subsection{Seasonal and non-stationary extremal dependence}\label{sec:lit-seasonal}

Allowing dependence to differ between winter and summer is a restricted form of non-stationary extremal dependence, with season as a binary covariate. Rather than fit a single covariate-dependent max-stable process, the thesis estimates one Brown--Resnick model per season and compares their parameters. This is a simple device, but it addresses a concrete concern: a single model fitted to all daily maxima would mix large-scale winter storms with localised summer convection, blurring exactly the contrast of interest. Anisotropic and space-time Brown--Resnick extensions exist --- \citet{buhl2016} estimate an anisotropic space-time version --- and are noted as directions the isotropic, season-by-season design here does not pursue. In what follows, \citet{padoan2010} and \citet{huser2013} supply the estimator, \citet{kabluchko2009} the model, \citet{dombry2016} the exact simulation used to validate the estimator, and \citet{cooley2006} and \citet{coles1999} the diagnostics.
