% CITATION KEYS: buhl2016 schlather2002 davison2013 huser2020.
% =====================================================================
\section{Conclusion}\label{sec:conclusion}

This thesis estimated season-specific Brown--Resnick spatial extremes models for daily maximum wind gusts at KNMI stations, to compare the spatial range of extremal dependence between winter and summer. After standardising each station--season margin to a common unit-Fr\'echet scale, the dependence parameters \(\vartheta_c=(\rho_c,\alpha_c)\) were estimated separately by season using pairwise composite likelihood (Section~\ref{sec:meth-cl}), and the range difference \(\rho_{\mathrm W}-\rho_{\mathrm S}\) was tested by a seasonal-year block bootstrap (Section~\ref{sec:meth-inference}). The Brown--Resnick process is used as a parametric approximation to the season-specific dependence, not as a verified data-generating mechanism.

\subsection{Summary of findings}\label{sec:conclusion-summary}

% TODO: 1--2 short paragraphs answering the research question after the
%        pipeline has run. State the simulation finding first (whether
%        the estimator and the one-sided test recover a known seasonal
%        difference at the empirical sample size and geometry), then the
%        empirical finding: estimated rho_W and rho_S, the sign and size
%        of Delta_rho, and whether H0: rho_W = rho_S is rejected against
%        H1: rho_W > rho_S. Use "the estimates suggest" rather than
%        "proves". Note whether the diagnostics of Section
%        \ref{sec:meth-diagnostics} support the fitted model. Do not draw
%        climate-change conclusions.

\subsection{Limitations}\label{sec:conclusion-limitations}

The main limitations follow from the model and the data. The Brown--Resnick process is asymptotically dependent at all finite distances, whereas the daily maxima may be asymptotically independent; if the diagnostics of Section~\ref{sec:meth-diagnostics} show dependence weakening at the highest levels, the fitted range overstates dependence in the extreme tail. The variogram is isotropic, so dependence is a function of distance alone; prevailing storm direction could make it anisotropic, and this is examined only as a robustness check. Daily maxima within a multi-day storm remain serially dependent, which does not bias \(\widehat\vartheta_c\) but inflates its variance; the seasonal-year bootstrap is used precisely to reflect this in the reported uncertainty, but with on the order of \(35\) season-years per season the intervals are wide. The marginal standardisation introduces estimation error that the fully parametric inference ignores and the bootstrap absorbs. Finally, the estimates are conditional on the observed, irregular station network, and \(\rho\) is identified only over the distances that network spans.

\subsection{Future work}\label{sec:conclusion-future}

Several extensions follow directly. An anisotropic or space-time Brown--Resnick model \citep{buhl2016} would relax the isotropy assumption and use the temporal structure of storms rather than treating daily fields as exchangeable within a season. A single covariate-dependent model with season as a covariate would replace the estimate-separately-by-season design and let the seasonal contrast be tested within one fit. Comparison with the Schlather \citep{schlather2002} or extremal-\(t\) classes, and with asymptotically independent alternatives \citep{davison2013,huser2020}, would test how far the conclusion depends on the Brown--Resnick specification. Extending the network with additional stations or gridded reanalysis fields would improve identification of \(\rho\) at longer distances.
